<li><a href="/printmail/article/173521/obamas-crackdown-whistleblowers"><img src="/sites/default/modules/custom/nation_theme/images/button-sharebar-email.jpg"></a></li>
<li><div class="text-size">
  <img src="/sites/default/modules/custom/nation_theme/images/button-sharebar-text-size.jpg">
  <img class="text-size-toggle text-size-dec" src="/sites/default/modules/custom/nation_theme/images/button-sharebar-text-size-dec.gif" alt="Decrease text size" title="Decrease text size">
  <img class="text-size-toggle text-size-inc" src="/sites/default/modules/custom/nation_theme/images/button-sharebar-text-size-inc.gif" alt="Increase text size" title="Increase text size">
</div></li>
<li><a href="https://subscribe.thenation.com/servlet/OrdersGateway?cds_mag_code=NAN&amp;cds_page_id=105997&amp;cds_response_key=I11BSPRV1"><img src="/sites/default/modules/custom/nation_theme/images/button-sharebar-subscribe.jpg"></a></li>
<li class="last"></li>
</ul></div>  <div id="wysiwyg">

<p><img alt="" src="/sites/default/files/user/205986/obama_stern_econ_ap_img.jpg" style="width: 615px; height: 410px;"><br><em>(AP Photo/Pablo Martinez Monsivais)</em><br>
	&nbsp;<br>
	In the annals of national security, the Obama administration will long be remembered for its unprecedented crackdown on whistleblowers. Since 2009, it has employed the World War I&ndash;era Espionage Act a record six times to prosecute government officials suspected of leaking classified information. The latest example is <a href="http://www.rollingstone.com/politics/lists/the-new-political-prisoners-leakers-hackers-and-activists-20130301/john-kiriakou-19691231">John Kiriakou</a>, a former CIA officer serving a thirty-month term in federal prison for publicly identifying an intelligence operative involved in torture. It&rsquo;s a pattern: the whistleblowers are punished, sometimes severely, while the perpetrators of the crimes they expose remain free.&nbsp;</p><div id='article-left-sidebar' style='clearfix'><div class="views-separator"> </div><div class="clearfix"><p>Research support provided by the Investigative Fund of the Nation Institute.</p>
</div></div><div id="body-block-left">  <div id="block-views-authors-block_3" class="block block-views">

      <h3>About the Author</h3>
  
  <div class="content">
    <div class="view view-authors view-id-authors view-display-id-block_3 view-dom-id-1">
    
  
  
      <div class="view-content">
        <div class="about-the-author">
<h5>
  <a href="/authors/tim-shorrock">Tim Shorrock</a>
</h5>
<div class="blurb">
  Tim Shorrock, who has been contributing to The Nation since 1983, is the author of Spies for Hire: The Secret World of...</div>
<!--/blurb-->
           
</div>
    </div>
  
  
  
  
  
  
</div>   </div>

</div>
  <div id="block-views-authors-block_1" class="block block-views">

  
  <div class="content">
      <div id="block-views-articles-block_6" class="block block-views">

      <h3>Also by the Author</h3>
  
  <div class="content">
    <div class="view view-articles view-id-articles view-display-id-block_6 view-dom-id-3">
    
  
  
      <div class="view-content">
        <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first clear">
    <div class="views-field-title">              
  <a href="/article/175604/obamas-militaristic-tilt-korea">Obama's Militaristic Tilt in Korea</a>  <span class="subject-topic">(<a href="/section/barack-obama">Barack Obama</a>, <a href="/section/regions-and-countries">Regions and Countries</a>, <a href="/section/us-military-presence-abroad">US Military Presence Abroad</a>)</span>
</div>
<!--/views-field-title--> 
<div class="blurb">
  <!--paging_filter--><p>At ceremonies held around the sixtieth&nbsp;anniversary of the Korean armistice, the president sounded bellicose notes, while failing to mention national unification.</p>
</div>
<div class="views-field-value byline">
 <a href="/authors/tim-shorrock">Tim Shorrock</a>
</div>
<!--/views field value-->
<div class="clear"></div>
  </div>
    <div class="views-row views-row-2 views-row-even views-row-last clear">
    <div class="views-field-title">              
  <a href="/article/174746/modern-day-stasi-state">A Modern-Day Stasi State</a>  <span class="subject-topic">(<a href="/section/us-intelligence">US Intelligence</a>, <a href="/section/war-profiteering">War Profiteering</a>)</span>
</div>
<!--/views-field-title--> 
<div class="blurb">
  <!--paging_filter--><p>Thanks to whistleblower Edward Snowden, we now know that an army of private contractors can monitor anyone&rsquo;s phone calls and e-mails.</p>
</div>
<div class="views-field-value byline">
 <a href="/authors/tim-shorrock">Tim Shorrock</a>
</div>
<!--/views field value-->
<div class="clear"></div>
  </div>
      </div>
  
  
  
  
  
  
</div>   </div>

</div>
  </div>

</div>
</div>
<p>The hypocrisy is best illustrated in the case of four whistleblowers from the <a href="http://www.nsa.gov/">National Security Agency</a>: Thomas Drake, William Binney, J. Kirk Wiebe and Edward Loomis. Falsely accused of leaking in 2007, they have endured years of legal harassment for exposing the waste and fraud behind a multibillion-dollar contract for a system called Trailblazer, which was supposed to &ldquo;revolutionize&rdquo; the way the NSA produced signals intelligence (<a href="http://www.fas.org/irp/doddir/dod/d5100_20.htm">SIGINT</a>) in the digital age. Instead, it was canceled in 2006 and remains one of the worst failures in US intelligence history. But the money spent on this privatization scheme, like so much at the NSA, remains a state secret.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The story goes back to 2002, when three of the whistleblowers&mdash;Loomis, Wiebe and Binney&mdash;asked the Pentagon to investigate the NSA for wasting &ldquo;millions and millions of dollars&rdquo; on Trailblazer, which had been chosen as the agency&rsquo;s flagship system for analyzing intercepted communications over a smaller and cheaper in-house program known as ThinThread. That program was invented by Loomis, one of the NSA&rsquo;s top software engineers, and Binney, a legendary crypto-scientist, both of whom began working for the NSA during the Vietnam War. But despite ThinThread&rsquo;s proven capacity to collect actionable intelligence, agency director Gen. Michael Hayden vetoed the idea of deploying the system in August 2001, just three weeks before 9/11.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Hayden&rsquo;s decisions, the whistleblowers told <em>The Nation</em>, left the NSA without a system to analyze the trillions of bits of foreign SIGINT flowing over the Internet at warp speed, as ThinThread could do. During the summer of 2001, when &ldquo;the system was blinking red&rdquo; with dangerous terrorist chatter (in former CIA Director George Tenet&rsquo;s famous words), they say the agency failed to detect critical phone and e-mail communications that could have tipped US intelligence to Al Qaeda&rsquo;s plans to attack.&nbsp;</p>
<p>&ldquo;NSA intelligence basically stopped in its tracks when they canceled ThinThread,&rdquo; says Wiebe, sitting next to Binney at an Olive Garden restaurant just a stone&rsquo;s throw from NSA headquarters in Columbia, Maryland. &ldquo;And the people who paid for it were those who died on 9/11.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>The NSA Four are now speaking out for the first time about the corporate corruption that led to this debacle and sparked their decision to blow the whistle. In exclusive interviews with <em>The Nation</em>, they have described a toxic mix of bid-rigging, cronyism and fraud involving senior NSA officials and several of the nation&rsquo;s largest intelligence contractors. They have also provided an inside look at how Science Applications International Corporation (<a href="https://www.saic.com/">SAIC</a>), the government&rsquo;s fourth-largest contractor, squandered billions of dollars on a vast data-mining scheme that never produced an iota of intelligence.&nbsp;</p>
<p>&ldquo;That corruption was the heart of our complaint&mdash;the untold treasure spent on a program that never delivered,&rdquo; Drake explained to me one morning in Bethesda, Maryland, across the street from the local Apple Store where he now works. He wants it understood that the NSA Four&rsquo;s case was not primarily about President Bush&rsquo;s warrantless domestic surveillance program, as outrageous as that was. &ldquo;Some in the press think we blew the whistle on Trailblazer because, oh, it violated people&rsquo;s rights,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Well, it didn&rsquo;t violate anybody&rsquo;s rights, or create any intelligence, because it never delivered anything.&rdquo;</p>
<p>But there&rsquo;s a direct link between their case and domestic spying: the technology developed at the NSA to analyze foreign SIGINT&mdash;including programs created for ThinThread&mdash;was illegally directed toward Americans when the agency radically expanded its surveillance programs after the 9/11 attacks. In response, Drake, Wiebe and Binney have taken to the media to expose and denounce what they say is a vast and unconstitutional program of domestic surveillance and eavesdropping.&nbsp;</p>
<p>By using the NSA to spy on American citizens, Binney told me, the United States has created a police state with few parallels in history: &ldquo;It&rsquo;s better than anything that the KGB, the Stasi, or the Gestapo and SS ever had.&rdquo; He compared the situation to the Weimar Republic, a brief period of liberal democracy that preceded the Nazi takeover of Germany. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re just waiting to turn the key,&rdquo; he said.&nbsp;</p>
<p align="center">* * *</p>

</div>
